Say a little bit.

00:35:14.490 --> 00:35:16.130
PAVNI DIWANJI: I think a better
way to ask the question

00:35:16.130 --> 00:35:17.080
is, how do you balance--

00:35:17.080 --> 00:35:21.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:21.160 --> 00:35:22.220
KIM POLESE: I grew up dancing.

00:35:22.220 --> 00:35:25.600
I grew up here in
the Bay Area.

00:35:25.600 --> 00:35:28.170
I discovered ballet
when I was 14.

00:35:28.170 --> 00:35:29.400
I just never stopped dancing.

00:35:29.400 --> 00:35:31.440
And it's always kept me sane.

00:35:31.440 --> 00:35:34.430
What's great about dance, any
form of dance, is that it

00:35:34.430 --> 00:35:35.770
takes total focus.

00:35:35.770 --> 00:35:42.120
You can't just zone out and run
on a stationary or cycle a

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:42.980
stationary bike.

00:35:42.980 --> 00:35:45.700
You have to actually be
memorizing choreography.

00:35:45.700 --> 00:35:49.950
You have to be thinking about
every movement of your body,

00:35:49.950 --> 00:35:51.730
and position the arms,
and so forth.

00:35:51.730 --> 00:35:54.390
And it's also incredibly
physically demanding.

00:35:54.390 --> 00:35:56.190
It kicks your butt.

00:35:56.190 --> 00:35:59.930
And so that's been
this wonderful--

00:35:59.930 --> 00:36:04.280
really literally-- balance in my
life, and a counterpoint to

00:36:04.280 --> 00:36:06.630
a very intense professional
life.

00:36:06.630 --> 00:36:11.380
And for me, what I've realized
is that everyone needs

00:36:11.380 --> 00:36:14.140
something that they're
passionate about outside of

00:36:14.140 --> 00:36:16.550
what you do every day,
especially if you're in a very

00:36:16.550 --> 00:36:18.590
intense work environment.

00:36:18.590 --> 00:36:22.080
And dance has been
that for me.

00:36:22.080 --> 00:36:25.680
MEGAN SMITH: It's interesting,
just because getting--

00:36:25.680 --> 00:36:27.150
doing exercise--

00:36:27.150 --> 00:36:29.700
and most of the tech
companies have

00:36:29.700 --> 00:36:31.150
workout places, et cetera.

00:36:31.150 --> 00:36:33.250
But to think about that a little
bit differently, as you

00:36:33.250 --> 00:36:35.120
have, which is take something
that you've been passionate

00:36:35.120 --> 00:36:38.040
about as a young person and are
exceptionally great at,

00:36:38.040 --> 00:36:44.120
because I know your dancing,
and to keep that going as a

00:36:44.120 --> 00:36:47.055
parallel track for the classic
like, let me go run on the

00:36:47.055 --> 00:36:48.110
treadmill, which is also good.

00:36:48.110 --> 00:36:50.060
But it's a really different
way of approaching it.

00:36:50.060 --> 00:36:50.735
KIM POLESE: Yes.

00:36:50.735 --> 00:36:53.165
MEGAN SMITH: I just thought it
was a very interesting thing.

00:36:53.165 --> 00:36:54.680
PAVNI DIWANJI: I have
