00:37:07.880 --> 00:37:12.340
So what advice would you give to
our young women developers

00:37:12.340 --> 00:37:16.330
who are either entering tech
or have just entered tech?

00:37:16.330 --> 00:37:17.836
KIM POLESE: Go for it.

00:37:17.836 --> 00:37:19.670
You're better than you
think you are.

00:37:19.670 --> 00:37:25.630
And the opportunities
are just infinite--

00:37:25.630 --> 00:37:28.360
the opportunity to found a
company, to build a company,

00:37:28.360 --> 00:37:32.090
to lead a project, to
change the world.

00:37:32.090 --> 00:37:36.040
And we need more women
technologists and women in

00:37:36.040 --> 00:37:39.580
general, women leaders
doing that.

00:37:39.580 --> 00:37:42.020
MEGAN SMITH: Kim and I were
just in England for the

00:37:42.020 --> 00:37:43.110
Silicon Valley Comes
to the UK.

00:37:43.110 --> 00:37:45.990
And we were at Bletchley Park,
which is-- and we have these

00:37:45.990 --> 00:37:49.510
books, which is the amazing
place where they cracked the

00:37:49.510 --> 00:37:52.510
Enigma codes during
World War II.

00:37:52.510 --> 00:37:54.920
And what was so interesting to
learn about this extraordinary

00:37:54.920 --> 00:37:57.160
place and the work that was
done-- and really the founding

00:37:57.160 --> 00:37:59.110
of the modern computer
industry was there.

00:37:59.110 --> 00:38:00.840
Alan Turing was there--

00:38:00.840 --> 00:38:03.110
was that it was half women
and half men, and such an

00:38:03.110 --> 00:38:04.730
amazingly diverse group.

00:38:04.730 --> 00:38:06.500
KIM POLESE: Exactly.

00:38:06.500 --> 00:38:08.410
MEGAN SMITH: And so
we were lucky to

00:38:08.410 --> 00:38:09.860
meet some of the veterans.

00:38:09.860 --> 00:38:12.015
And they were totally
passionate, women and men in

00:38:12.015 --> 00:38:12.590
their nineties.

00:38:12.590 --> 00:38:14.330
KIM POLESE: Yes.

00:38:14.330 --> 00:38:15.340
MEGAN SMITH: Awesome.

00:38:15.340 --> 00:38:17.020
KIM POLESE: So inspirational.

00:38:17.020 --> 00:38:19.940
MEGAN SMITH: And I think
sometimes people don't realize

00:38:19.940 --> 00:38:21.460
the kinds of teams we're in.

00:38:21.460 --> 00:38:23.540
They think somebody's coding
all alone or something.

00:38:23.540 --> 00:38:24.660
But it's really--

00:38:24.660 --> 00:38:25.980
the tech industry is amazing.

00:38:25.980 --> 00:38:29.520
We hope that more people, young
men and young women,

00:38:29.520 --> 00:38:30.620
will join us.

00:38:30.620 --> 00:38:31.520
KIM POLESE: Yeah, absolutely.

00:38:31.520 --> 00:38:32.430
In fact, you're right.

00:38:32.430 --> 00:38:37.720
I think people don't realize how
social it is, the process

00:38:37.720 --> 00:38:40.000
of creating and building
technology.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.830
It's very much about teams and
interactions of teams.

00:38:42.830 --> 00:38:47.210
And the importance of diversity
in really bringing

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:51.160
all different views and
approaches is so critical and

00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:51.920
often overlooked.

00:38:51.920 --> 00:38:54.400
And it's actually one of things
I love about Google is

00:38:54.400 --> 00:38:55.870
that you guys have really
prioritized

00:38:55.870 --> 00:38:57.440
that from the beginning.

00:38:57.440 --> 00:39:00.480
And Bletchley Park is definitely
worth a visit if

00:39:00.480 --> 00:39:01.620
you're ever in the UK.

00:39:01.620 --> 00:39:04.660
MEGAN SMITH: 45 minutes of
train ride from London.

